{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1aa7cbbc-fee6-406c-a6a5-e396c7d2762e","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request lifecycle. The DI scope is tied to the app's `IServiceProvider`, which lives for the entire application lifetime. This means your scoped `DbContext` effectively behaves as a **singleton** — the same instance is reused across all page navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives each injection a fresh `DbContext`.\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory<T>`** and create/dispose contexts manually:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then in your view model:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n3. **Create explicit scopes** with `IServiceScopeFactory` if you need to control the lifetime more precisely.\n\nOption 2 (`IDbContextFactory`) is the recommended pattern for MAUI/Blazor/desktop apps where there's no natural per-request scope.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"16c0f21b-8944-4acf-b022-4c22c293e7c1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so scoped services behave essentially like singletons — the scope is the entire application lifetime (or at least very long-lived).","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"A848:2AD648:710D63:824E2F:69FBE509"},"id":"133b337c-187a-49c4-bf9b-86e76e610fee","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:04:19.788Z","parentId":"ee9b649b-1c66-46f2-9765-4adf518cb9ab"}
